      <p class="note" style="font-size:0.8rem; color: var(--color-muted);">* Embassy times vary month to month. Check Visa Appointment Wait Times at travel.state.gov for the most current data for your specific post.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="factors">
      <h2>What Affects Your Processing Time?</h2>
      <div class="factors-grid">
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">📋</div>
          <h4>Quality of your initial filing</h4>
          <p>A complete, well-organized petition with strong evidence is less likely to receive an RFE. An RFE can add 3–6 months to your timeline.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">🌍</div>
          <h4>Your fiancé's country</h4>
          <p>Embassy workload and staffing levels vary enormously. High-volume posts like Manila or Ciudad Juárez consistently have longer queues than lower-volume posts.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">🏢</div>
          <h4>USCIS service center assigned</h4>
          <p>You can't choose your service center. Cases are assigned based on USCIS's internal workload balancing. CSC and TSC tend to run slower than NSC.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">🔍</div>
          <h4>Background checks &amp; security</h4>
          <p>Name checks against national security databases can hold a case for weeks or months if there are matches — even if innocent.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">📅</div>
          <h4>Time of year</h4>
          <p>USCIS typically slows in December due to holiday staffing. Embassy appointment availability also fluctuates with local conditions and U.S. federal holidays.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">📜</div>
          <h4>Prior immigration history</h4>
          <p>Prior visa denials, overstays, or removal orders involving either party trigger additional review and typically extend processing times.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="check-status">
      <h2>How to Check Your Case Status</h2>
      <ul class="check-steps">
        <li class="check-step">
          <div class="check-step-num">1</div>
          <div class="check-step-body">
            <h4>USCIS stage — my.uscis.gov</h4>
            <p>Use your receipt number (starts with EAC, WAC, LIN, or MSC) to check your I-129F status at <a href="https://my.uscis.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">my.uscis.gov</a>. The status will show "Case Received," "Case Is Being Actively Reviewed," or "Case Was Approved." You can also sign up for email/SMS notifications.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="check-step">
          <div class="check-step-num">2</div>
          <div class="check-step-body">
            <h4>After USCIS approval — check if NVC received it</h4>
            <p>Call the NVC at 603-334-0700 or email NVCInquiry@state.gov with your USCIS receipt number to confirm they received your case. Give it 4–6 weeks after the USCIS approval before inquiring.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="check-step">
          <div class="check-step-num">3</div>
          <div class="check-step-body">
            <h4>Embassy stage — contact the specific post</h4>
            <p>Once the embassy has your case, contact them directly for interview scheduling timelines. Most embassies have appointment scheduling portals or email inquiry systems. Check the specific embassy's website for their process.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="check-step">
          <div class="check-step-num">4</div>
          <div class="check-step-body">
            <h4>If stuck — congressional inquiry</h4>
            <p>Contact your U.S. Representative or Senator's office (the petitioner's Congressional district). Most have immigration caseworkers who can submit a formal congressional inquiry to USCIS. This often moves stuck cases. It's free and legal — use it.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="after-entry">
      <h2>After the K-1 Visa: The 90-Day Clock</h2>
      <p>Once your fiancé enters the U.S. on the K-1 visa, a 90-day clock starts. You <strong>must marry within those 90 days</strong>. After marriage, you file for Adjustment of Status (Form I-485) to get the green card.</p>
      <p>The AOS process adds another 12–24 months and approximately $1,440 to the total cost. Factor this into your overall timeline planning.</p>

      <table class="sc-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Phase</th><th>Timeline</th><th>Key Form</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>I-129F filing to USCIS approval</td><td>7–14 months</td><td>I-129F</td></tr>
          <tr><td>NVC transfer</td><td>3–6 weeks</td><td>—</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Embassy interview + visa issuance</td><td>1–3 months</td><td>DS-160</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Entry to U.S. + marriage</td><td>Within 90 days</td><td>—</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Adjustment of Status (green card)</td><td>12–24 months</td><td>I-485</td></tr>
          <tr style="font-weight:700; background: var(--color-surface);"><td>Total: Filing to green card</td><td>24–42 months</td><td>—</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How long does the K-1 visa take in 2026?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The total K-1 process takes approximately 12–18 months from filing to visa in hand: 7–14 months for USCIS to approve I-129F, 3–6 weeks for NVC, and 1–3 months for embassy processing. This does not include the subsequent Adjustment of Status process after marriage (additional 12–24 months).</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How do I check my K-1 case status?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">During USCIS processing, use your receipt number at my.uscis.gov. After USCIS approves and transfers to NVC, contact NVC at 603-334-0700 or NVCInquiry@state.gov. For embassy status, contact the specific U.S. embassy or consulate where your fiancé will interview.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why is my K-1 taking so long?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The most common reasons are: USCIS backlog at your service center, an RFE (Request for Evidence) that paused the clock, name check holds, or prior immigration issues triggering additional review. If you've passed the published processing time, submit a case inquiry at my.uscis.gov or contact your congressional representative.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can I speed up my K-1 visa processing?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">There is no premium processing (expedite) available for I-129F. You can request expedited processing from USCIS only in very specific circumstances — severe financial loss, emergency, or humanitarian reasons — and approval is rare and discretionary. The best way to minimize delays is to file a complete, well-documented petition from the start.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Does a K-1 RFE mean my petition will be denied?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">No. An RFE is a request for more information, not a denial. Most RFEs result in approval after the petitioner provides the requested documents. Respond completely and within the stated deadline (typically 87 days). If the RFE is complex, consider consulting an immigration attorney for the response.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is the K-1 or CR-1 faster in 2026?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">To get your partner physically in the U.S., the K-1 is usually faster (12–18 months vs. 14–24 months for CR-1). However, the CR-1 bypasses the 12–24 month Adjustment of Status process after arrival. For total time to green card, the CR-1 is often comparable or faster. See our <SmartLink href="/k1-vs-cr1">K-1 vs CR-1 comparison</SmartLink> for a full breakdown.</div>
      </div>
    </section>

